metadata.name: Midfile Crisis #201
metadata.description:
Midfile Crisis is about realizing halfway through you are not gonna make it.

The struggle is real.

-

The work itself is the union of 2 projects, which, well, didn’t make it. Together though, they are stronger than ever. So yes, Midfile Crisis is a love story, too.

-

Procedural , ever changing real-time animation, October 2022
Javascript and WebGL

-

FEATURES

- 6 color palettes, inspired by recent artworks by Xenia Hausner, Ayako Rokkaku, Jenny Saville, Amy Sherald, Sue Williams and Emily Xie, are referenced accordingly. One additional, rare color palette will slowly cycle through the full color spectrum.
- Direction: Up, Right, Up Right
- Seed: Up, Right, Up Left
- Shape Tendency: Tetra, Box, Sphere, Octa, Ico, Multi
- Amount: Low, Medium, High

VIEWING

- The artwork is in landscape format, please click on open to see the full frame and resolution. We recommend rotating your screen on mobile.
- Press 'i' to show artwork title and features.
- Press 's' to save an image.
- To guarantee the same output at different resolutions the simulation driving the artwork is locked at 1024x512 pixels. To unlock, press 'u' - this can help when running at a lower resolution and the animation is not smooth, or when running at significanly higher resolutions and pixelation is starting to occur. Please note this will break the deterministic nature of the work.
- Best viewed in Chrome Desktop with dedicated GPU.
- Please note: requires latest devices (supporting WebGL2) for a smooth experience.

metadata.name: {Lumina} #2145
metadata.description:
The restitution of a breath
Your breath is your artwork

{Lumina} is part of the installation Σ Lumina taking place at Musée d’Orsay. A free live minting is scheduled from February 13th to March 10th, 2024. 

Breath, the vital essence, embodies our interconnection. It carries our shared heritage. A medium that helps Σ Lumina to unite the physical and the digital, the living with the coded. The voices of Orsay resonate within us, their breath becoming ours, landscaping our common creation.


Art curators of {Le Code d’Orsay}:
Christophe Leribault,
Président de l’Établissement public du musée d’Orsay et du musée de l’Orangerie
Virginie Donzeaud, Administratrice générale adjointe

16x16
HTML, js, Webgl
Location: Musée d’Orsay

metadata.name: Mareas del Ser #56
metadata.description:
'Mareas del Ser' encapsulate the ever-changing essence of the human experience. This art collection reflects the duality between chaos and calmness that defines our lives. Much like the ocean tides, our experiences ebb and flow, bringing forth moments of turmoil and tranquility.

These artistic pieces delve into the peaks and valleys, the challenges, and the moments of peace that compose our life's journey. Through brushstrokes, lines, and shapes, they express internal struggles and the ongoing quest for balance amidst emotional storms, seeking inner calm amidst external bustle.

'Mareas del Ser' prompt reflection on how we navigate these changes, learn from adversity, and uncover stillness within chaos. Each artwork serves as a testament to human resilience, showcasing the beauty of finding stability in impermanence and discovering peace amidst constant transformation.

Features:
30 Path Variations.
11 Color Palette.
8 Types of Frames.
3 Types of Textures.

Press "S" to download the image 3000 x 4000.

Created by Fernando Cabral.  License CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

metadata.name: (DE)STRUCTURAL #33
metadata.description:
"Reserve a spot for your family and loved ones in our brand new *floating* high rise condominiums. Leave the dirty air of Level-1 behind! Discount of 200'000'000 credits applicable is you already own any of our apartments in another sector."

Like with my previous works, each variation starts as an empty black canvas in the depth of your [CALCULATING MACHINE]. With your [UNIQUE PURCHASE TRANSACTION RECEIPT] specially constructed AI engineers start to envision a condominium that is perfect just for you! Utilizing both the [CENTRAL PROCESSING UNIT] and [GRAPHICS PROCESSING UNIT] the blueprints materialize in front of your [ORGANS OF VISION OR OF LIGHT SENSITIVITY]. Everything is procedurally generated taking in hundreds of randomized parameters bound to specific rules of construction.

Orbit: mouse [PRIMARY] button.
Pan: mouse [SECONDARY] button.
Zoom: mouse [GYRATION DISC].
Cycle light intensity levels: [B]

metadata.name: La Invernada #33
metadata.description:
This project is about my mother's lifestyle. Her work is breeding and herding goats, cows and horses.
She lives a cyclical life marked by two major stages during her livestock year: "La Veranada" and "La Invernada". My last work was about "La Veranada", this work is about "La Invernada", I hope you enjoy it.
Time in the life of a criancero is cyclical. Everything comes and goes, and comes back and comes back. Nature, so present, so in connection with the man and woman who inhabit it, marks the times perhaps like no other place.
 The succession of the seasons, the weather, the buds and "La Invernada", the sowing, the pastures, the harvest and the snows.
"La Invernada" is the place during what we could call the long winter, that is, from April to November.
"La Invernada" is down in the plains, in the pampas, in accessible places, where it is easy to supply forage to the goats that calve between October and November.
The "Criancero" rides a horse every day and, accompanied by his dogs, goes to "watch" the goats. They distinguish them in the distance. Every day is the same and different at the same time. Caring for, watching over and keeping the goats healthy and safe.
"El puesto" is their home. In the stall they use the water from the river, which they draw with a water pump, for their hygiene. Water for consumption is brought in jerry cans from "Vertientes", located about 10 km away.
 The hens roam freely throughout the day, when night comes some go to sleep in the "gallinero" and others simply sleep on small plants.
As you can see, life here is simple, solitary and with a lot of work.
I want to thank all those who have taken the trouble to read the story. I hope you liked it.
You can find real photos and videos of "La Invernada" on my twitter profile.

Features:
10 Color Palettes.
10 types of Animal pen.
Various types of chickens.
14 types of herbs.
10 types of flowerpot.
4 types of trees.
7 types of rivers.
The barn has 4 sizes.
The moon has a very varied range of x and y positions.
6% chance of getting snowy weather in the piece.

Note that the algorithm may take some time to run.
Created by Fernando. NFT 2.0 license.

metadata.name: Dithered Nostalgia #155
metadata.description:
Have you ever struck by a sudden surge of nostalgia?
Making you stop everything you did at that moment,
Trying hard to remember the memory behind it, and failed to do so?

Each of these lands hold a nostalgia unlocked,
Like how good nostalgia are, it’s dithered and full of holes.
Holes that can be filled with your own memories and interpretations.

• • •

The second collaboration of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. This time using MEK.txt’s landscape pixelart series and its distinctive dithering textures, brilliantly translated into code by IceRain to pixel-perfect iterations.

Dithered Nostalgia is a step up from MEK.txt & IceRain’s first project (Bento Boxes), trying to make more sophisticated, more detailed and challenging things based on something they passionate about; landscape.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: contrapuntos #676
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #966
metadata.description:

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
